For a team to determine who they should draft, or how much they should be paying each of their players, it's important for them to know what trends lead to success in the league. Because of this, our aim in this project is to determine what statistic leads to overall success in the league. For the purposes of this project, we are disregarding playoffs, and considering the winning team to be the one with the most wins in the regular season.

During the course of the NBA, it's clear that there have been many changes in how the game is played, which leads to a lot of discourse over who the greatest player of all time would be. Because of this, we're going to be mapping out each of the seasons from 1980 to 2020, along with how different statistics correlate to success within the league. This will help us determine the overall trends within the league

Step 1) Pulling the Data¶

The first step is going to be to pull the information from the website basketball-reference.com as a starting point we're going to be pulling from the "Team Stats" table, available for each of the seasons.¶

While browsing the basketball-reference.com page, we were able to find that website presents each of the pages in a way that makes it easy to scrape programmatically.

In [10]:
baseurl ="https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_" 
yearurl= 1980
endurl = ".html"
leaguestats = []
while (yearurl < 2022):
    r = requests.get(baseurl + str(yearurl) + endurl)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(r.text, 'lxml')
    commentedout = []
    for comment in soup.find_all(text = lambda text:isinstance(text,Comment)):
        commentedout.append(comment)
    for element in commentedout:
        if str(element).startswith('\n\n<div class="table_container" id="div_team-stats-base">'):
            #print(commentedout.index(element))
            correctindex = commentedout.index(element)
    newsoup = BeautifulSoup(commentedout[correctindex], 'html.parser' )
    leaguestats.append(pd.read_html(str(newsoup).replace("*",'')))
    yearurl+=1

The leaguestats array will contain a dataframe for each season, accessible through leaguestats[{targetyear} - 1980]¶

The information available is as follows, and is a total for that season:

G => Games Played | MP => Minutes Played | FG => Field Goals (a basket scored on any shot or tap other than a free throw)

FGA => Field Goal Attempts | FG% => Field Goal Percentage | 3P => 3-Point Field Goals

3PA => 3-Point Field Goal Attempts | 3P% => 3-Point Field Goal Percentage | 2P => 2-Point Field Goals

2PA => 2-Point Field Goals Attempts | 2P% => 2-Point Field Goal Percentage | FT => Free Throws

FTA => Free Throw Attempts | FT% => Free Throw Percentage | ORB => Offensive Rebounds | DRB => Defensive Rebounds

TRB => Total Rebounds | AST => Assists | STL => Steals | BLK => Blocks | TOV => Turnovers | PF => Personal Fouls

PTS => Points

In [12]:
baseurl ="https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_" 
yearurl= 1980
endurl = ".html"
miscstats = []
while (yearurl < 2022):
    r = requests.get(baseurl + str(yearurl) + endurl)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(r.text, 'lxml')
    commentedout = []
    for comment in soup.find_all(text = lambda text:isinstance(text,Comment)):
        commentedout.append(comment)
        #print(comment)
    for element in commentedout:
        if str(element).startswith('\n\n<div class="table_container" id="div_misc_stats">'):
            #print(commentedout.index(element))
            correctindex = commentedout.index(element)
    newsoup = BeautifulSoup(commentedout[correctindex], 'html.parser' )
    miscstats.append(pd.read_html(str(newsoup).replace("*",'')))
    yearurl+=1

Step 2) Graph the averages over the seasons¶

In order to determine which statistic has a higher correlation with the success of a team in a particular season, the first step should be to determine the average of that statistic each year, and plot that average.

From there, we would be able to determine how the winning and losing teams in the league compare to the league average.

In [40]:
# miscstats and leaguestats contain the averages of all the data presented for each season
#Leaguestats
#3P => 3-Point Field Goals
#3PA => 3-Point Field Goal Attempts
#3P% => 3-Point Field Goal Percentage
# FGA => Field Goal Average
# FG% => Field Goal Percentage

YrHiRank = []
YrLoRank = []
fig1, ax = plt.subplots()
for i in range(len(miscstats)):
    # Because miscstats sorts by the team's rank in the season, we can pull the 
    # highest ranking team's information for each season by grabbing the head of that 
    # season's dataframe
    head = miscstats[i][0].head(1)['Team']
    YrHiRank.append(head[0])
    for i in miscstats[i][0]['Team']:
        # We use a similar approach to what was described above in order to pull
        # the lowest ranking team
        if i != 'League Average':
            tail = i
    YrLoRank.append(tail)
#print(YrLoRank)
years = []
HiStat = []
LoStat = []
for i in range(1980,2022):
    years.append(i)
ssn3pa = []
for i in range(len(leaguestats)):
    #We then plot the average, the highest ranking team, and the lowest ranking team
    for j in leaguestats[i][0]['Team']:
        if j == YrHiRank[i]:
            stat = leaguestats[i][0][leaguestats[i][0]['Team'] == j]
            HiStat.append(float(stat['3PA']))
            
        if j == YrLoRank[i]:
            stat = leaguestats[i][0][leaguestats[i][0]['Team'] == j]   
            LoStat.append(float(stat['3PA']))
                    
    leagueAttmptStat = float(leaguestats[i][0]["3PA"].tail(1))
    ssn3pa.append(leagueAttmptStat)
    
fig1.set_size_inches(10, 10, forward=True)
ax.plot(years,HiStat,'o')
ax.plot(years,LoStat,'^')
ax.plot(years,ssn3pa)
plt.title('3-Point Field Goal Attempts Per Year')
plt.xlabel('Years')
plt.ylabel('3PA')
ax.legend(['Winners','Losers','league averages'])

Modifying our Approach¶

As you can see, there are sharp dips in every statistic in both 1998-1999 season, and 2011-2012 season. After seeing this, and looking closely at the data, we saw that there was in NBA lockout for both of those seasons. For the 1998-99 season, that resulted in the season being shortened to 50 regular season games per team. For the 2011-12 season, it resulted in the season being shortened to 66 regular season games per team.

In order to avoid having a skew in our data, we decided to change our approach to being per game. That will allow us to view the league average per game, which would not be as affected by the lockout. However, it's important to note that although the data is then normalized by the per game approach, it does not change that the players themselves might have been affected by the lockout, which may be reflected by a change in performance during that season.

    for j in pergamestats[i][0]['Team']:
        if j == YrHiRank[i]:
            stat = pergamestats[i][0][pergamestats[i][0]['Team'] == j]
            HiStat.append(float(stat['AST']))
            
        if j == YrLoRank[i]:
            stat = pergamestats[i][0][pergamestats[i][0]['Team'] == j]   
            LoStat.append(float(stat['AST']))
    leagueAvrgPerc = float(pergamestats[i][0]["AST"].tail(1))
    SznStat.append(leagueAvrgPerc)
    yrMax.append(pergamestats[i][0]['AST'].max())

    
fig1, ax = plt.subplots()
fig1.set_size_inches(10, 10, forward=True)
ax.plot(years,HiStat,'o')
ax.plot(years,LoStat,'^')
ax.plot(years,yrMax,'x')

ax.plot(years,SznStat)
plt.title('League Average Assists Per Game Vs Year')
plt.ylabel('Assists')
plt.xlabel('Years')
ax.legend(['Winner','Loser','Max','league averages'])
